Certainly! Below is a LaTeX formatted table that includes three lesser-known cities in Spain, their renowned festivals, and the historical background and significance of each festival.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{array}
\usepackage{geometry}
\geometry{margin=1in}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
    \begin{tabular}{| m{4cm} | m{4cm} | m{7cm} |}
    \hline
    \textbf{City} & \textbf{Festival} & \textbf{Historical Background and Significance} \\ \hline
    Haro & Batalla del Vino & The Batalla del Vino, or Wine Battle, takes place on June 29th, coinciding with the feast day of San Pedro. This tradition dates back to the 13th century and involves participants dousing each other in red wine. The festival symbolizes the long-standing wine-producing culture of the La Rioja region and celebrates the joy of the local community. \\ \hline
    Buñol & La Tomatina & Held on the last Wednesday of August, La Tomatina is a tomato-throwing festival that started in 1945. It began as a spontaneous act of revelry among locals and has since become an international spectacle. The festival represents the playful spirit and camaraderie of the Buñol community and attracts visitors from around the world. \\ \hline
    Laza & Entroido & Entroido in Laza is one of the oldest and most traditional Carnival celebrations in Galicia. The festival features unique customs, including the peliqueiros, masked figures who maintain order. Dating back to pre-Christian times, Entroido represents the community’s rich cultural heritage and the transition from winter to spring, filled with vibrant rituals and festivities. \\ \hline
    \end{tabular}
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

This table provides an overview of each city's unique festival, along with insights into their cultural and historical contexts. You can compile this LaTeX code to see the formatted table.
